-- ds.h1: FifthTry

During my search, I came across [`FifthTry`](https://www.fifthtry.com/), and their product immediately caught my attention. I was curious about the company as a whole, and what impressed me most was their commitment to continuously improving their product. While their documentation may have been rough around the edges, I was impressed that they had the confidence to make it publicly available using their own product.

Team at`FifthTry` has an ambitious goal of developing a new open-source, front-end programming language, `FTD`, a language for everyone. 
`FTD` allows anyone to create visually appealing documents and user interfaces with just a few lines of code. It is easy to read and understand, and less verbose than HTML while being more flexible than Markdown. 


-- quote.marengo: FifthTry

Our language is specifically designed for human beings, not just programmers.


-- ds.markdown:

Team at `FifthTry` not only just created a stand-alone lanuage but they have build a full stack on top of it; `fastn`. To read more about `FTD` and `fastn` [click here.](https://fastn.io/overview) 


-- ds.image:
src: $assets.files.images.initiative.jpg

-- ds.h1: My initiative

I knew this was an opportunity I couldn't pass up. Although I had no prior experience in this specific role, I was always fascinated and was eager to jump in and begin contributing to the team's mission. After exploring the documentation on `FTD`, I found that there were no structured learning courses available to help me learn the language beyond the written documentation.

I took the initiative and used the available resources to create a `Hello World` program. I recorded myself doing this and reached out to `AmitU`, the CEO of `FifthTry` to share my progress. He was impressed with the video and I suggested that the company could benefit from having a video course to help others learn the language.

I am currently work as a **DevRel** - Intern at `FifthTry`.
As an intern, I am still learning and growing in my role, but I am passionate about the work I am doing and excited to be part of such an innovative company and to help create the course and promote the language to a wider audience. 


